caption: The food is absolutely amazing. A true Haitian treat!!! Everything is so tasty!!! Thanks guys. See you again...and, soon!

I Was visiting BK and wanted to dive in to some Haitian food to bring me back to home cooking. The food was nothing like a Haitian meal. I was very disappointed and actually embarrassed of the quality that this restaurant is branding to be from my culture.  The rice was bland, chicken dry, amount of food scarce, no beautiful colors, sauce was made straight from a tomato can. I Didn’t even stay 10min to force myself to eat before asking a togo bag to then 🚮 it. Sorry Kombit- but please don’t brand yourself to be Haitian food.

I went there twice with my boyfriend for a date night and secondly for a grab and go and I fell in love with their chicken wings and their sauce. They are crispy and well flavored. My boyfriend had a legume, which was good too the first time but don’t forget to grab some wings even after a long day of work lol

I'm pretty sure the ratings are so high because of the NON-Haitian customers (delusional) . I ate here back when I first move back home, and wanted to see what this gentrified part of BK had to offer.  I recommend heading toward Flatbush if you want quality as opposed to pandering flavors. $40 for rice & beans (bland), lambi (again bland) and a soda lacaye. Nah bruh NAH!  I get that it's located in faux mini Manhattan but at least match the quality when it comes to flavors js!

If you enjoy Haitian food or are interested in trying it, I'd recommend paying this restaurant a visit.  It's not fancy,  in fact,  it's a bit of a hole-in- the- wall. There's a cozy, island feeling when you're there and the home cooked-esque meals complete the experience. The staff are great, friendly, welcoming and are more than happy to offer a few recommendations just in case you're feeling indecisive or totally clueless on what to choose.  This restaurant is in a prime location,  near the Barclay Convention Center so it's a good option after a concert,  event or day of shopping.  You're missing out if you're in the area and pass this place by.  Try it out. You won't be disappointed!

Up until I went here I was never the biggest fan of Haitian food. Thanks to Kombit that has officially changed. The food is truly delicious, I enjoyed every little bite. Everything was freshly prepared, from the homemade fruit juices to the appetizers to the main course. But I guess all that comes at a cost, everything took so dam long to come out. Literally got there at 9 and didn’t leave until 12, the chef really takes their sweet little time back there in the kitchen. The service wasn’t the best either, I mean I know it’s Caribbean restaurant but all the attitude can be saved for the behind the counter take out spots, not at an actual sit down restaurant. The prices seemed a little high in my opinion and they automatically add gratuity. Definitely might only be good for takeout.

I happened upon this restaurant on a night of very inclement weather, initially stopping in to have a drink and dry-off at their cozy little bar. The generous hospitality of the Proprietors was also something I never will forget.

I went with my brother on a quiet weeknight, for dinner and a chat. I ordered griot with diri, and a couple prestige beers.  The food was good, fried pork is always good, especially deep fried. And the diri was an interesting and pleasant experience. Prestige beer is nothing fancy, but the food is a recommend.  Service was prompt and useful, without being in your face. There wasn't a lot of vocal explanation of the dishes, but I felt the menu descriptions were good.  Good food, chill vibe, I would go again
